"M Room," a listening operation which elicited information of the same significance and scope as Bletchley Park. Yet the work of Kendrick, and its full significance, remains largely unknown. Helen Fry draws on extensive original research to tell the story of this remarkable British intelligence officer. Kendrick’s life sheds light on the development of MI6 itself—he was one of the few men to serve Britain across three wars, two of which while working for the British Secret Service. Fry explores the private and public sides of Kendrick, revealing him to be the epitome of the "English gent"—easily able to charm those around him and scrupulously secretive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEspionage, BritishxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpieszGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSecret servicezGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073923740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300262971?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262971/original  a978-3-11-073923-7  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles